author: David Bateman
title: Blue Jays fans pumped and anxious ahead of Game 5 against Rangers
text:
Fans across Toronto, Canada and the world will be watching as the Blue Jays look to prolong their first post-season in 22 years.
With the American League Division Series against the Texas Rangers tied 2-2, it’s once again “do or die” for Josh Donaldson & Co.
In Toronto, thousands will join a blue procession along Front St. from Union Station as early as 1 p.m.
Those not lucky enough to score tickets to the Rogers Centre game will join the swelling ranks of the Bird’s Nest, a.k.a. Nathan Phillips Square.
Across Canada, families abandoned and altered Thanksgiving plans Sunday and Monday to catch the Jays’ games. Once again, they’ll find ways to skip work or covertly watch on their phones.
Jays fans living abroad — some even in Texas — who had shown their support during games three and four, prepared to go through another nail-biting nerve-jangler.
Dillon Rahkola, a Torontonian now living in Adelaide, Australia, will be waking early to watch the game, as he has done for the rest of this series.
On Twitter, other fans had voiced their support from Jamaica and Italy during game four.
Jays fans everywhere are all-in for the biggest baseball game in Toronto since the World Series of 1993.
